    <h1>Chapter Five: The Central River</h1>
    <p class="lede">The Central River is the wide river that runs through the Rim from sea to sea.</p>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">World rule</p>
      <h2>The river shapes the Rim</h2>
      <p>The Central River is not a small local river. It is one of Vaelinya’s major world-shaping features: a long, wide river that cuts across the Rim and connects distant coasts, crossings, settlements, memories, and routes.</p>
      <p>People use it for travel, trade, warning, song, meeting, and return. Its banks are places where stories gather because many lives pass through them.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Reader use</p>
      <h2>What to notice</h2>
      <p>When the Central River appears in a story, it usually means more than water. It can mark a boundary, a route, a promise, a danger, a memory, or a way for separated places to remain connected.</p>
      <p>For Lina, the river matters because she notices crossings carefully. A river crossing is never only a shortcut. It asks who is travelling, what they carry, and what changes when they reach the other side.</p>
    </article>

